<HEADLINE>
Pledges for Lebanon donor conference in Paris
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
2007-01-25 08:43:41 UTC
</P>
<P>
A brief look at which countries are planning to pledge what aid
to Lebanon at a donor conference in Paris on Thursday:
</P>
<P>
UNITED STATES -- U.S. Secretary of State Condoleezza Rice said
the Bush administration is seeking US$770 million (euro592
million) in new aid for Lebanon. The money, which must be
approved by Congress, would finance long-term redevelopment and
immediate rebuilding from last year's devastating war between
Hezbollah militants and Israel.
</P>
<P>
FRANCE -- Conference host pledging a loan of euro500 million
(US$650 million) at "very advantageous" terms.
</P>
<P>
EUROPEAN UNION -- European Commission pledging euro400 million
(US$522 million) in new aid and loans.
</P>
<P>
SOUTH KOREA -- Reluctant to offer fresh donation beyond the
US$5.5 million (euro4.2 million) pledged last year.
</P>
<P>
FINLAND -- Expects to donate "somewhat smaller amount" than the
euro4.5 million it gave in 2006.
</P>
<P>
MALAYSIA -- Foreign Minister Syed Hamid Albar told The Star that
Malaysia would not make a new loan because it loaned US$500
million four years ago.
</P>
<P>
BRITAIN -- Plans to offer $40 million (euro30 million) to UNIFIL
in 2007-2008 financial year.
</P>
<P>
DENMARK -- Planning extra support of 20 million kroner (euro2.7
million; US$3.5 million) for mine-clearance, aid and implementing
U.N. resolution 1701.
</P>
<P>
CHINA -- Promising "assistance within our capacity."
</P>
<P>
JAPAN -- Promising new aid on top of US$7 million already pledged
since last July. New total will exceed US$10 million (euro7.7
million), the Foreign Ministry said.
</P>
